==English==

===Etymology===
Compound of ''smoke'' + ''fall''.

===Noun===
'''smokefall'''

# The close of the day before [[nightfall]], when fog comes.
<!--
  "The moment in the draughty church at smokefall"
    -- T.S. ELIOT, Four Quartets 1: Burnt Norton (1935)
  [http://www.tristan.icom43.net/quartets/norton.html]
-->
# The permanent twilight that could result from a nuclear war.
<!-- Seen used in physics papers about nuclear winter. -->
# A falling cloud of smoke from a large fire.
<!-- [http://hpwren.ucsd.edu/news/031118.html] -->
# An artificial waterfall of smoke, for shows.

